'''''King Arthur's Quest''''' is a first-person perspective [[graphic adventure game|graphic adventure]] [[interactive fiction]] video game developed by Five Ways Software and published by Hill MacGibbon for the [[ZX Spectrum]] in 1984.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.crashonline.org.uk/12/news.htm|title=CRASH 12 - News|website=www.crashonline.org.uk|access-date=2018-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/personalcomputergames-magazine-14|title=Personal Computer Games Magazine Issue 14}}</ref> There was also a canceled [[Commodore 64]] version.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gamesthatwerent.com/gtw64/king-arthurs-quest/|title=King Arthur's Quest|date=2012-10-03|work=Games That Weren't|access-date=2018-06-14|language=en-US}}</ref>

== Plot ==
The game casts the player in the role of [[King Arthur]] of [[Camelot]]. The evil witch [[Morgan le Fay|Morgana Le Fey]] has cast an icy shroud spell on the land since Arthur has refused to accept her son [[Mordred]] as one of the [[Knights of the Round Table]]. Furthermore, [[Lancelot]], Arthur's best knight, has mysteriously vanished. Arthur goes to ask his old friend [[Merlin]] for his help, but he finds the magician's home finds it empty except for Merlin's talking cat then accompanies Arthur on his quest.

The game world contains eight areas: Merlin's Tower, the Wilderness, the Enchanted Forest, the Keep, the Chapel, the Crypt, the Cavern, and Morgana's Keep. Eventually, Arthur finds and rescues the enchanted Merlin, who defeats Morgana and lifts her curse.

==Reception==
The game received mostly positive reviews, such as in ''Micro Adventurer'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/MicroAdventurer13-Nov84|title=Micro Adventurer Issue 13|last=Sunshine Books|date=November 1984|language=en}}</ref> ''TV Gamer'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/TV_Gamer_1985-01_Boytonbrook_GB|title=TV Gamer (1985-01)(Boytonbrook)(GB)|date=January 1985}}</ref> and ''[[Your Computer (British magazine)|Your Computer]].''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/your-computer-magazine-1985-03|title=Your Computer Magazine|date=March 1985}}</ref> However, some others have been negative, such as in ''[[Big K (magazine)|Big K]]''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/Big_K_Issue_10_1985_Jan|title=Big K Issue 10 1985 Jan}}</ref> and ''[[Sinclair User]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/sinclair-user-magazine-034|title=Sinclair User Magazine Issue 034|date=January 1985}}</ref>

